## From Compliance Training to Behavioral Security

Day 91 documented the policy architecture — fully developed policies, policies in development, and policies that exist only as SSP references without standalone governance documents. The policy section identified the Acceptable Use Policy as a material gap in the insider threat deterrence architecture (RS-005), and the change management policy as a second-year priority driven by the M-002 and A-7 compliance pattern. It also surfaced a principle that connects directly to today's section: a policy that no one has been formally presented with and acknowledged is not an enforceable policy.

The same principle applies to training. Training that confirms completion but does not measure behavioral change is not security awareness — it is compliance documentation. The distinction between these two is something the OpenMRS program encountered directly: AT-2 training completion is at 100%, which satisfies the HIPAA administrative safeguard requirement for security awareness and training. But the Day 79 self-assessment found that one of two staff members could not describe the downtime procedure after completing the contingency plan training. One hundred percent completion, approximately fifty percent behavioral retention for the specific procedure tested.

Day 92 develops the training program that the capstone's second year needs to build — starting from what year one established, honest about what year one did not demonstrate, and specific about what a behaviorally effective training program looks like for a healthcare NGO with OpenMRS on AWS.

