## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified the training section today is the distinction between security training and security behavioral change.

Security training delivers information. Security behavioral change produces different decisions under real conditions. The distinction is not academic — it is the difference between a staff member who completed a module about phishing and a staff member who, when a targeted phishing email arrives at 9am during a busy clinical morning, pauses before clicking and takes 15 seconds to verify the sender.

The conditions under which the training is tested are never the conditions under which it was delivered. Training is delivered in a controlled, low-pressure environment — a computer module with clear prompts and obvious correct answers. The real attack arrives when the staff member is between patients, the inbox shows 47 unread messages, and the phishing email is specifically crafted to look like a message from the Health IT Manager about a system update.

This is why the phishing simulation program is not a nice metric to have — it is the only mechanism that tests whether the training has produced behavioral change under realistic conditions. Every month without a phishing simulation is a month in which the organization asserts its training is effective without any evidence that it is.

