### Quarterly Awareness Campaign Design

The quarterly awareness campaigns are not training — they are reinforcement. Brief, specific, relevant to the current threat environment.

**Q1 second year:** "Why Your TOTP Code Is the Last Line of Defense" — connecting MFA to the HC3 credential theft briefing. Two paragraphs, one concrete example, one specific action request (never share your TOTP code, even with IT staff asking for it).

**Q2 second year:** "What Happens After You Click" — following the first phishing simulation, a brief explanation of what the simulation found, what it means, and what to look for. Positive framing: this is how we get better together.

**Q3 second year:** "The Downtime Procedure — Could You Do It at 2am?" — contingency plan retention reinforcement. One page, laminated, posted at the clinical workstation. Not a training module. A reference card.

**Q4 second year:** "Year-End Security Reflection" — aggregate metrics from the year's monitoring program. Not a compliance report. A brief, accessible summary: here is how the security program performed, here is what improved, here is what we are working on. Treats staff as partners in the security program, not subjects of it.

