## The Human Layer as a Security Control

Looking at the complete control set from Day 90 alongside the training program, the human layer is both the most difficult to monitor and the most important for the current threat environment. The technical controls (MFA, WAF, encryption, Config monitoring) address the opportunistic attacker — the one who is looking for easy targets and will move on if the first obstacle is robust. The human layer addresses the targeted attacker — the one who is specifically trying to compromise MyClinic's OpenMRS system and is willing to invest in a convincing phishing email to do it.

The HC3 briefing that elevated RS-001 and RS-004 from Moderate to High described targeted campaigns, not opportunistic scanning. Targeted campaigns go through people because that is often the path of least resistance through good technical controls. A staff member who recognizes and reports a targeted phishing attempt stops the attack at the first step — before the attacker ever reaches the technical controls.

This is what the Day 90 control gap analysis described as "the human layer as the single highest-priority gap in the current control set." The phishing simulation program and the quarterly retention checks are the mechanisms for closing that gap systematically — not through a single training intervention, but through ongoing measurement and reinforcement that builds genuine security intuition over time.

