## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The behavioral gap between training completion and effective response under real conditions is illustrated precisely by the **2020 Twitter Bitcoin scam**, in which attackers used social engineering — phone calls impersonating IT support — to convince Twitter employees to provide their VPN credentials. Twitter's employees had security training. They presumably understood that credential sharing was prohibited. Under real-time social pressure from a convincing impersonator, several employees complied.

The Twitter case is relevant to the OpenMRS training program not because the attack vector is identical but because it demonstrates the core behavioral gap: employees who know the rule in a training context may not apply it reliably under the time pressure and social dynamics of a real attack. The phishing simulation program specifically tests this — it creates a low-pressure real-world analog to the actual attack, measures the behavioral response, and provides just-in-time feedback when the behavior needs correction.

For the OpenMRS program, the quarterly awareness campaign topic "never share your TOTP code, even with IT staff asking for it" addresses exactly the Twitter attack vector — social engineering that creates urgency and legitimacy to extract a credential. Staff who have seen this framed explicitly, rather than just completing a phishing recognition module, are better positioned to resist it.

